                <h3>How Infections Work</h3>
                <p>Infectious agents have a wide range of methods used to get inside the human body and cause an infection, such as airborne movement through coughing and sneezing, infected body fluids, fecal contamination of food and water and injuries allowing germs past the skin. Once inside the body, germs multiply and colonise areas they are suited to, surviving using methods like producing toxins which damage and break down nearby host cells, producing bacterial biofilms that stop immune cells and drugs from reaching the colony, viruses and small bacteria hiding inside host cells, and worms burrowing through tissues and releasing anti-inflammatory chemicals to weaken the immune system. While some bacteria are capable of moving on their own and can spread easily through the body if not contained by the immune system, others are immobile and spread slowly through tissues until they reach the bloodstream and get carried around, causing sepsis.</p>
                <p>The immune system is responsible for preventing and fighting infections, resulting in mild to no symptoms of disease if successfully able to destroy or contain the germs, or more severe disease if the infection overwhelms the immune system, potentially requiring medical intervention with drugs to treat the infection. The immune system has two main parts, innate immunity and adaptive immunity. Innate immunity is the first line of defense against foreign pathogens and mainly involves phagocytic cells like macrophages and neutrophils, which engulf and dissolve pathogens, natural killer T cells which detect and destroy abnormal cells likely to be virus-infected or cancerous, and chemicals like complement proteins and defensins which bind to pathogens and destroy or mark them. Adaptive immunity follows the innate immune response and involves lymphocyte cells like B cells, which recognise specific pathogens and produce matching antibodies that bind to them, and T cells which kill pathogens marked by antibodies. This response is also directed towards all types of infections from foreign pathogens to virus-infected or cancerous cells. The adaptive immune system creates long-lived memory cells that remember pathogens from previous infections, producing an immune response more efficiently when the same infection happens again and clearing it faster.</p>
