                <h3>First Recorded Diseases</h3>
                <p>Throughout history, humanity has faced many different kinds of diseases, some more deadly than others. TB is the oldest contagious disease known to affect humans, with early TB progenitors being found in early human fossils as far back as 20,000-15,000 years ago, and TB deformities found in Egyptian mummies dating back to 2400 BC. TB was also documented in India, China, Ancient Greece and Rome, and was known as both scrofula and consumption in the Middle Ages depending on which of its various symptoms appeared, then the "white plague" in the 18th century due to its effect on patients' appearance. Later on, the Plague of Athens around 430 BC was the first recorded pandemic and occurred during the Peloponnesian War between Athens and Sparta, causing significant disruption in Athens which was already overloaded by siege and refugees at the time. While the symptoms including pustular rash, high fever and diarrhea were well-documented, the plague itself was not definitely identified and could have been typhus, smallpox or another unknown disease.</p><br />
