                <h3>Significant Pandemics and Outbreaks</h3>
                <p>Epidemics and Pandemics are a phenomenon caused by the increasing density of human populations, shared use of resources and ability to travel freely allowing diseases to spread more easily. One of the first major pandemics to affect humanity on a large scale was the Black Death, caused by bubonic and later pneumonic plague that significantly reduced the global population. Another major and global pandemic was Spanish Flu, caused by the influenza virus during WW1 and of unknown origin despite the name, killing more individuals than the Black Death in a short time and unusually affecting young and healthy individuals worse. Smallpox was a deadly and highly infectious disease that also led to Edward Jenner's development of the world's first vaccines, and became the first and only disease to be eradicated. Mad Cow Disease was an unusual disease in the 90s' caused by infectious proteins (prions) transmitted by Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE)-infected cattle being used in cattle feed and later beef supply. SARS emerged as the first severe outbreak of the 21st century, spreading easily through air travel and requiring vigilance from medical authorities to successfully control and prevent its spread. As of 2024, Covid-19 caused by the SARS_CoV-2 virus is the latest global pandemic on an unprecedented scale, requiring drastic action from governments and medical researchers, as well as rapid development of effective vaccines and treatments which are still ongoing.</p><br />
