                <h3>Early Misconceptions of Disease Causes Before Germ Theory</h3>
                <p>Common beliefs in early human history were that disease was caused by supernatural events or divine punishment for crimes. Later on, observation-based theories such as those from Ancient Greece attempting to explain why disease occurred became more common, though still flawed. Humours theory incorrectly stated that four body fluids, blood, yellow bile, black bile and phlegm needed to be in balance and would cause disease when out of balance, leading to practices like bloodletting to restore 'balance'. Miasma theory originating in the Middle Ages and persisting into the 20th century held that decaying matter and other causes of bad smells produced miasma, bad air which would cause people to become sick by breathing it. This resulted in ineffective solutions like attempting to clean air instead of removing sewage and cholera-contaminated water that was causing disease. The plague doctor mask and gown used by doctors in the 17th century also attempted to prevent plague infection supposedly caused by miasma, without success. While miasma theory was incorrect, the association of sewage with disease was later linked to disease-causing microorganisms.</p><br />
