                <h3>Germ Theory and Epidemiology</h3>
                <p>The modern understanding of microorganisms as the causative agent of infectious disease, started with the invention of the microscope by a Dutch spectacle-making team in 1590, then Anton von Leeuwenhoek who observed bacteria in 1675, then Koch's Postulates in the 19th century were used to prove that certain microorganisms would cause disease when put in a living animal. Later on, John Snow and the Broad Street water pump's link to the cholera epidemic became one of the founding events of epidemiology, which would correlate contaminated material rather than miasma with disease, even if the theory was ignored at the time in favour of miasma. Another major finding was the discovery of viruses in the 1890s when microbiologists observed infectious particles in fluid that could pass through a bacterial filter. There are also a variety of other disease-causing agents like parasites and fungi.</p><br />
