                <h3>Cancer</h3>
                <p>A disease caused by body cells growing out of control, cancer was observed as far back as Ancient Egypt and is still a major problem today, having a range of causes both genetic and environmental but generally the result of DNA mutation. Cancer starts off as normal body cells accumulating mutations to the point where they become abnormal, growing and multiplying out of control instead of following regular cell growth signals. While cells have a number of built-in systems to detect and stop the abnormal growth, and the immune system regularly destroys lots of abnormal cells, mutations in most to all these systems simultaneously can allow cancer cells to progress. One common check system includes a cell division maximum which causes abnormal cells to form a benign tumour, often seen as a lump in the body which stops growing after a while but may become big and press on nearby organs. Limited by lack of space, anti-growth signals, self-destruction signals, lack of new blood vessels to supply the tissue and immune cells detecting and destroying abnormal cells, these tumours often will not become cancerous. However, further mutations that allow these tumours to continue growing unchecked, produce new blood vessels and evade or disable immune cells, results in cancerous tumours that grow constantly. This becomes severe when the cells gain the ability to metastasise (Stage 4 cancer), invading nearby tissues and replacing functional organ cells with cancer cells. Metastatic cells can also break off from the main tumour, enter the bloodstream and travel around the body to form new tumours. While the immune system is good at recognising and destroying cancer cells which often display abnormal cell features, sometimes immune cells are unable to recognise the cancer cells which appear too similar to normal cells, or the cancer cells produce signal molecules that disable the immune cells. Cancer mutations and abnormal tumour features like the low-oxygen center of large tumours can also result in resistance to some cancer drugs. Although difficult to treat, current treatments like chemotherapy, radiotherapy and immunotherapies like monoclonal antibodies and CAR T-cell therapy can often destroy cancers, and modern cancer research has produced promising future treatments which can cure metastatic treatment-resistant Stage 4 cancer.</p><br />
