                <h3>Mutation</h3>
                <p>DNA is the genetic code that defines the features of cells and how they behave. However, there are a range of factors that can result in mutations changing ths code. DNA replication as part of normal cell division sometimes has errors that result in permanent changes. Damage to DNA by free radicals, radiation, mutagenic chemicals and UV results in DNA repair mechanisms that may not always correctly replace the damaged sections, resulting in mutations. DNA viruses that insert themselves into host DNA can also cause mutations. Many mutations have no effect if they occur in non-functional sections of DNA, such as disabled genes or guide sections which do not produce proteins. However, some mutations will introduce new features or activate genes that were previously disabled, potentially causing problems.</p>
