                <h3>Antibiotic Resistance</h3>
                <p>Along with its effect on human history, TB is also notorious for antibiotic resistance, being very difficult to treat and sometimes requiring a combination of drugs to treat, which can also have severe side effects on patients. MRSA is another well-known bacterium which frequently causes difficult-to-treat infections in hospitals due to its resistance to penicillin antibiotics, especially the commonly-used methicillin and the improved versions used later. Bacteria can mutate over time as a natural process, changing their features over generations and potentially gaining resistance to antibiotics which can accumulate over time and even transfer to other bacteria through plasmid DNA. These measures include bacterial membranes or cell walls which prevent uptake of the antibiotics, biofilms that trap antibiotics, efflux pumps that pump antibiotics back out of the bacterium, altered bacterial components that prevent antibiotics from attaching, and chemicals or enzymes that disable antibiotics. As antibiotics occur in nature as defensive features used by bacteria and fungi against other microorganisms, microbes have also evolved to be resistant to these. Misuse of antibiotics further worsens the antibiotic resistance issue, meaning healthcare providers have to be careful when administering antibiotics and patients careful when using them. Antibiotic resistance is more likely to develop when patients do not complete the prescribed full course of antibiotics or take antibiotics when they do not need it, like for a viral infection, potentially resulting in some bacteria with partial antibiotic resistance surviving and evolving increasing resistance until the antibiotic is ineffective against them. An issue with antibiotics becoming ineffective is that medical research companies have slowed the development of more effective antibiotics and discovery of new classes is expensive and not easy, meaning research into other areas like natural bactericidal compounds and bacteriophage therapy are also being investigated. Viruses are not alive and cannot be affected by antibiotics, though antivirals can inhibit their spread.</p><br />
